s the Temple of Marquis Wu, Huiling, and various historical exhibitions.</p> <p><strong>Travel tips:</strong> It's advisable to hire a professional guide or use an audio guide to better understand Three Kingdoms history. Allow approximately 2 hours for the visit. Avoid the midday hours; morning or afternoon visits are more comfortable. If you're interested in Three Kingdoms history, consider allocating more time for a detailed exploration.</p> <h3>Wide and Narrow Alleys</h3> <p>The Wide and Narrow Alleys consist of three parallel old streets: Wide Alley, Narrow Alley, and Well Alley, forming the most complete preservation of Qing Dynasty streets in Chengdu. The area retains many courtyard-style old mansions and has now become a representative locale of Chengdu's leisure lifestyle, integrating dining, leisure, entertainment, and culture.</p> <p><strong>Travel tips:</strong> The Wide and Narrow Alleys can get crowded, so it's advisable to visit on weekdays, as weekends and holidays tend to be more congested. The area features many elegant cafes and teahouses, perfect for resting and experiencing Chengdu's slow-paced lifestyle. Try traditional ear-cleaning services or gaiwan tea to experience authentic Chengdu tea culture.</p> <h3>Mount Qingcheng-Dujiangyan</h3> <p>Mount Qingcheng is one of the birthplaces of Taoism in China, renowned for its tranquil natural scenery and numerous Taoist temples. The adjacent Dujiangyan is the world's oldest existing, still-functioning, barrage-free water diversion project, hailed as the 'Ancestor of World Water Conservancy Culture.'</p> <p><strong>Travel tips:</strong> Mount Qingcheng and Dujiangyan are close to each other and can be visited together in one day. It's recommended to visit Dujiangyan first, then proceed to Mount Qingcheng. Mount Qingcheng is divided into Front Mountain and Back Mountain; Front Mountain has concentrated attractions, more suitable for general tourists, while Back Mountain offers better natural scenery, ide