year showcase traditional Taoist culture.</p> <h3>Three Kingdoms Shu Han History</h3> <p>Chengdu was the capital of the Shu Han regime during the Three Kingdoms period, a history widely known through the novel 'Romance of the Three Kingdoms.' Historical figures like Liu Bei, Guan Yu, Zhang Fei, and Zhuge Liang had close connections with Chengdu, leaving behind numerous historical sites.</p> <p><strong>Historical footprints:</strong> Wuhou Temple is an important site commemorating Zhuge Liang, Prime Minister of Shu Han, and includes the Temple of Emperor Liu (honoring Liu Bei) and Huiling among its building complex. Liu Bei established the Shu Han regime in Chengdu; Zhuge Liang administered Shu Han affairs, implementing policies like 'farming and studying for family heritage' and 'water conservancy development,' promoting regional development. This period of history not only influenced Chengdu's political and economic development but also enriched the local cultural context. Visitors can gain a deeper understanding of this magnificent historical period by visiting Wuhou Temple and reading relevant historical works.</p>', <h3>Chengdu Tea Culture</h3> <p>Chengdu's teahouse culture has a long history, dating back to the Tang and Song dynasties. As an important component of Chinese tea culture, Chengdu's teahouses are renowned for their unique social function and leisurely atmosphere.</p> <p><strong>Teahouse life:</strong> Chengdu's teahouses are not just places for tea drinking but centers for socializing, entertainment, and information exchange. Traditional teahouses typically offer gaiwan tea, supplemented with services like ear-cleaning, card-playing, and newspaper reading, providing a snapshot of old Chengdu life. Today, Chengdu still has thousands of teahouses, from traditional old-style establishments to modern boutique tea lounges, catering to different groups. The Heming Teahouse in People's Park is an ideal place to experience traditional teahouse culture, wher